			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_PBG-D</LocID>										<Text>Low PBG-D</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_PBG-D_DESCRIPTION</LocID>							<Text>Porphobilinogen deaminase (hydroxymethylbilane synthase, or uroporphyrinogen I synthase) is an enzyme that in humans is encoded by the HMBS gene. Porphobilinogen deaminase is involved in the third step of the heme biosynthetic pathway.</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_SPHEROCYTE</LocID>								<Text>Spherocyte</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_SPHEROCYTE_DESCRIPTION</LocID>					<Text>Discovery of spherocytes in the blood smear.</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_DEFICIT_GPI</LocID>								<Text>Low GPI</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_DEFICIT_GPI_DESCRIPTION</LocID>					<Text>Glucose-6-phosphate isomerase (GPI), alternatively known as phosphoglucose isomerase/phosphoglucoisomerase (PGI) or phosphohexose isomerase (PHI), is an enzyme that in humans is encoded by the GPI gene on chromosome 19. In the cytoplasm, the gene product functions as a glycolytic enzyme (glucose-6-phosphate isomerase) that interconverts glucose-6-phosphate (G6P) and fructose-6-phosphate (F6P).</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_DEFICIT_G6PD</LocID>								<Text>Low G6PD</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_DEFICIT_G6PD_DESCRIPTION</LocID>					<Text>Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD or G6PDH) is a cytosolic enzyme that helps protect the red blood cells against oxidative damage from compounds like hydrogen peroxide.</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_PK_BAS</LocID>									<Text>Low PK</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_PK_BAS_DESCRIPTION</LocID>						<Text>Pyruvate kinase is the enzyme involved in the last step of glycolysis.</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MORE_DG_TEST_COMBS_D</LocID>								<Text>Coombs +</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MORE_DG_TEST_COMBS_D_DESCRIPTION</LocID>					<Text>The Coombs test is positive.</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_DEFICIT_ADAMTS13</LocID>							<Text>Low ADAMTS13</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_DEFICIT_ADAMTS13_DESCRIPTION</LocID>				<Text>ADAMTS13 (a disintegrin and metalloproteinase with a thrombospondin type 1 motif, member 13)—also known as von Willebrand factor-cleaving protease (VWFCP)—is a zinc-containing metalloprotease enzyme that cleaves von Willebrand factor (vWf), a large protein involved in blood clotting.</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_DREPANOCYTE_A</LocID>								<Text>Drepanocyte</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_DREPANOCYTE_C</LocID>								<Text>Drepanocyte</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_DREPANOCYTE_DESCRIPTION</LocID>					<Text>Discovery of drepanocytes in the blood smear.</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_vWF</LocID>										<Text>Low vWF</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_vWF_DESCRIPTION</LocID>							<Text>von Willebrand factor (VWF) (/ˌfʌnˈvɪlɪbrɑːnt/) is a blood glycoprotein involved in hemostasis.</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>

