			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_CORTISOL_EFF_DESCRIPTION</LocID>						<Text>The cortisol level in the blood is very low.</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_TRANSPLANTATION_COEUR</LocID>							<Text>Transplant</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString>	<LocID>SYM_MOREDG_TRANSPLANTATION_COEUR_DESCRIPTION</LocID>				<Text>This patient urgently needs a heart transplant!</Text>	</GameDBLocalizedString>
				
			<!-- Fixed -->
			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_CRP_ATAXIA_CEREBELLAR</LocID> <Text>Cerebellar ataxia</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_CRP_ATAXIA_CEREBELLAR_DESCRIPTION</LocID> <Text>Impaired coordination and balance with a broad-based, unsteady stance or gait and difficulty with tandem walking.</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>

			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_CRP_HYPERSIGNAL_MAMILLAIRE</LocID> <Text>Mammillary body hyperintensity on MRI</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_CRP_HYPERSIGNAL_MAMILLAIRE_DESCRIPTION</LocID> <Text>T2/FLAIR hyperintensity of the mammillary bodies, often seen in thiamine deficiency (Wernicke encephalopathy).</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>

			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_CRP_HYPERTONIA</LocID> <Text>Hypertonia (increased muscle tone)</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_CRP_HYPERTONIA_DESCRIPTION</LocID> <Text>Abnormally increased muscle tone, commonly from upper motor neuron lesions; may present as spasticity or rigidity with hyperreflexia.</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>

			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_CRP_NYSTAGMUS_HORIZONTAL</LocID> <Text>Horizontal nystagmus</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_CRP_NYSTAGMUS_HORIZONTAL_DESCRIPTION</LocID> <Text>Involuntary side-to-side eye oscillations. Unidirectional patterns are often peripheral; direction-changing gaze-evoked nystagmus suggests a central lesion.</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>

			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_CRP_NYSTAGMUS_VERTICAL</LocID> <Text>Vertical nystagmus</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_CRP_NYSTAGMUS_VERTICAL_DESCRIPTION</LocID> <Text>Up- or down-beat ocular oscillations that typically indicate central pathology involving the brainstem or cerebellum.</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>

			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_CRP_PARALYSIA_OM_VI</LocID> <Text>Abducens (CN VI) palsy</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_CRP_PARALYSIA_OM_VI_DESCRIPTION</LocID> <Text>Paralysis of the lateral rectus muscle causing impaired eye abduction and horizontal diplopia.</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>

			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_CRP_POLYGON_UP</LocID> <Text>Wide-based stance/gait</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_CRP_POLYGON_UP_DESCRIPTION</LocID> <Text>Enlarged base of support while standing or walking, a typical compensatory sign of gait instability (e.g., cerebellar ataxia).</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>

			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_MOREDG_NEURO_B1_EFF</LocID> <Text>Neurologic effects of vitamin B1 deficiency</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_MOREDG_NEURO_B1_EFF_DESCRIPTION</LocID> <Text>Findings consistent with thiamine deficiency, classically confusion, ataxia, and ophthalmoplegia (Wernicke triad), with possible nystagmus.</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>

			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_MOREDG_NEURO_FLAPPING_TREMOR</LocID> <Text>Asterixis (flapping tremor)</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_MOREDG_NEURO_FLAPPING_TREMOR_DESCRIPTION</LocID> <Text>Brief lapses of sustained posture leading to irregular, flapping movements of the hands; often seen in metabolic encephalopathies (e.g., hepatic).</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>

			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_MOREDG_NEURO_PP_EFF</LocID> <Text>Neurologic effects of vitamin PP (niacin) deficiency</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>
			<GameDBLocalizedString> <LocID>SYM_MOREDG_NEURO_PP_EFF_DESCRIPTION</LocID> <Text>Niacin (vitamin B3/PP) deficiency can cause pellagra with neuropsychiatric features such as confusion, neuropathy, tremor, and cognitive changes.</Text> </GameDBLocalizedString>

